I"O<p>Never ever say you are a geek if you don’t have some mathematical formulas on your website! I have done so though <a href="http://www.mathjax.org">MathJex</a><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">:)</code>. Here are some examples:</p>

<p>Code:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>$$ x = {-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac} \over 2a} $$
$$ |s_n - s_m|=|\sum_{k=m+1}^n u_{k}|=|u_{m+1}+u_{m+2}+...+u_{n}| \lt \epsilon $$
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Result:</p>

<p><span>\(x = {-b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac} \over 2a}\)</span></p>

<p><span>\(|s_n - s_m|=|\sum_{k=m+1}^n u_{k}|=|u_{m+1}+u_{m+2}+...+u_{n}| \lt \epsilon\)</span></p>

<p>Now let’s try some inline formulas, such as you may except <span>(b \ne 0)</span> in expression <span>(a \over b)</span> and the famous formula <span>(E = mc^2)</span> from Einstein.</p>

<p>However, there are some issues to use MathJex with Markdown because symbols in formula will be parsed by Markdown first. The easiest way to avoid this is surrounding your formula with <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;span&gt;</code> since Markdown will parse nothing in a html/xml block. Such as <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;span&gt;\(a \ne 0\)&lt;/span&gt;</code> for a inline formula <span>(a \ne 0)</span>.</p>
